    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since you can't run heavy-duty memory profilers on the target hardware, you'll need to rely on more lightweight, in-situ monitoring techniques. You can use a system of \"memory checkpoints,\" which is a technique that relies on tracking the *difference* in memory usage between known good states, much like a very small, highly focused logging mechanism.\n\nFirst, you must adopt smart pointers everywhere—`std::unique_ptr` for exclusive ownership, and perhaps `std::shared_ptr` if you truly need shared ownership, though `unique_ptr` is usually the safer bet in embedded systems to prevent circular dependencies that cause leaks. If you're still using `new`, you need to wrap it in a custom allocator or use a memory pool, which is a much more robust solution for embedded systems than relying on the OS heap.\n\nFor monitoring, try implementing a simple heap tracking wrapper around `new` and `delete` (or your custom allocator). This wrapper doesn't need to track *what* is allocated, just *how much* is allocated and *how many* allocations are pending. Every time you call `new`, increment a counter and add the size to a running total. Every time",
      "source": "target",
