      "role": "user",
      "content": "The idea of a custom wrapper for `new`/`delete` sounds doable. I can probably implement a simple counter that logs to a serial port or a small circular buffer in telemetry. \n\nOne thing though—we've had issues in the past where the leaks don't always follow a predictable pattern. Sometimes they seem almost \"random\" or like they're hiding in specific edge cases that only trigger under very specific timing conditions. It’s really frustrating because it feels like these bugs are just lurking there, waiting for the exact right moment to mess everything up. \n\nWhen you're dealing with those kinds of elusive, hard-to-track-down issues, what's your mental model for hunting them? How do you keep from getting overwhelmed by the \"ghosts in the machine\" feeling when the telemetry just shows a slow, unexplained creep?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the leaks are behaving like elusive, unpredictable gremlins—the kind that only appear when the timing is just right—you're dealing with a classic race condition or a complex state management issue, which is far trickier than a simple forgotten `delete`. My mental model for hunting these ghosts is to stop looking at the *symptom* (the slow creep) and start looking at the *behavior* (the state transitions).\n\nThink of it like tracking a rogue packet through a network of tiny, interconnected, and often poorly guarded little tunnels. You can't just look at the final destination; you have to trace every single junction. The key is to impose *order* on the chaos, even if the chaos is timing-based.\n\nFirst, you must aggressively instrument the state machines. Every time a critical piece of data enters or leaves a module, log the *state* of that module, not just the data itself. If a sensor reading is processed, log: `[Time] [ModuleID] [State_Before] -> [State_After]`. If you see a transition that *should* lead to cleanup but doesn't, that's your target.\n\nSecond, introduce controlled stress",
